@chapter Files


@quotation

You can start @strong{it-edit} from the command line with a space delimited files list, as argument, which will be opened in the editor at start.

Or use the @strong{it-edit} icon with your files-manager you can select files to open with @strong{it-edit}.

To know for files managing:


@itemize +

@item 
@strong{Open a new empty file} use the menu item, the button or the shortcut: @strong{Ctrl + n}.

@item 
@strong{Open a file} by selecting it with a file selector, use the menu item, the button or the shortcut: @strong{Ctrl + o}.

@item 
You can @strong{open a recent file} by selecting it in the list from the menu item.

@item 
@strong{Save} the current editor content use the menu item, the button or the shortcut: @strong{Ctrl + s}.

@item 
@strong{Save all} open files use the menu item, the button or the shortcut: @strong{Ctrl + Maj + S}.

@item 
@strong{Reload file} will reload the last saved version from the file in the editor, use the menu item or the shortcut @strong{Ctrl + R}.

@item 
@strong{File informations} will display informations, which you can edit, about the current file, use the menu item or the shortcut @strong{Ctrl + I}.
@end itemize

You can easily navigate into your open files by using the pop-up menu or by clicking on the file tab.

You can reorder your open files as wanted by drag and drop the files tabs.
@end quotation

